SIMPLE: naturalize
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Naturalize
<hw>Nat"u*ral*ize</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Naturalized</conjf>
<pr>(#)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Naturalizing</conjf>
<pr>(#)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>naturaliser</ets>. See
<er>Natural</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make natural; <as>as,
custom <ex>naturalizes</ex> labor or study</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To confer the rights and privileges of a native
subject or citizen on; to make as if native; to adopt, as a foreigner
into a nation or state, and place in the condition of a native
subject.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To receive or adopt as native, natural, or
vernacular; to make one's own; <as>as, to <ex>naturalize</ex> foreign
words</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To adapt; to accustom; to habituate; to acclimate;
to cause to grow as under natural conditions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Its wearer suggested that pears and peaches might yet be
<qex>naturalized</qex> in the New England climate.</q>
<rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Naturalize</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Naturalize
<hw>Nat"u*ral*ize</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become as
if native.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To explain phenomena by natural agencies or laws, to
the exclusion of the supernatural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Infected by this <qex>naturalizing</qex> tendency.</q> <rj><qau>H.
Bushnell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>naturalized</ent>⟦br⟧
